ssed the Gobi Desert. His later expeditions into Russian Central Asia searched for the origins of agriculture and early civilization."},{"number":2,"category":"science","header":"He tied windblown dust to climate history","body":"Pumpelly's studies of loess, the fine wind-laid soil of northern China, helped show how such deposits record ancient climate. At home he directed the northern transcontinental railroad survey and led major government geological surveys."},{"category":"career","header":"He held Harvard's first chair in mining","body":"From 1866 to 1875 Pumpelly served as Harvard's first professor of mining, between expeditions that carried him around the world. He later organized the economic-geology division of the new U.S. Geological Survey and directed its New England branch.","number":3},{"category":"science","header":"His Anau dig pushed Central Asian history back","body":"In 1903 Pumpelly led a Carnegie-funded expedition to the Anau mounds in Turkmenistan, uncovering a settlement he dated to about 4500 BCE. The mineral pumpellyite, found in Michigan's copper country, was later named in his honor.","number":4},{"category":"legacy","header":"He blazed the Pumpelly Trail up Monadnock","body":"From his summer place at Dublin, New Hampshire, Pumpelly cut a ridge trail to the summit of Mount Monadnock that still carries his name. He spent his last decades at Newport and presided over the Geological Society of America in 1905.","number":5}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"descends from Springfield's founder William Pynchon","related_id":"Y00004","link_text":"Hon. William Pynchon"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"descends from Connecticut governor Thomas Welles","related_id":"X02354","link_text":"Gov. Thomas Welles"},{"type":"parallel_careers","display_label":"the mineralogist in whose system pumpellyite is class